observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
Require each AOs (the Collectors and the Municipal Treasurer) to prepare individual RAAFs;
Submit the individual RAAFs to the Audit Team;
Ensure that consolidated RAAF resulted from the consolidation of all the AOs’ individual RAAFs;
Ensure preparation and submission of these RAAFs in accordance with the cited regulations.

We recommended that the LDRRMO:
Evaluate the unutilized balances of the current year’s five per cent LDRRMF, continuing LDRRMF, and the unexpended LDRRMF transferred to the Trust Fund books;
Anticipate and promptly address issues and concerns affecting the efficient and effective implementation of LDRRM PPAs to avoid delays or non-implementation;
Maximize LDRRMF utilization focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management and consider the needs of the time, such as the COVID-19 emergency; and
Ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed and reprogrammed projects during the budget year to optimize the fund’s utilization and warrant that goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of the Local Government Unit (LGU’s) PPE annually;



Prepare and submit in a prescribed format a complete and accurate reports of Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) for the current year to the Municipal Accountant and the Commission on Audit (COA) before January 31 of the succeeding year; and

Reconcile the physical count of the PPE with book records and make necessary adjustments.

Review the schedules and subsidiaries to ensure proper presentation of schedules of accounts in the Financial Statements (FS);

Ensure that any funds accruing to the barangays of the Municipality are transferred to them on a timely basis;


Through the Municipal Treasurer, inform the parties with stale checks of their claim from the Municipality; and

Revert back to the GF payables falling under the criteria in Section 98 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445.

Avoid accepting eligibility requirements after the deadline of submission of bids;

Use non-discretionary pass/fail criteria especially during bid evaluation and/or opening of bids, and during post-qualification;

Ensure that all process and/or procedures before contract signing have taken place prior entering into contract;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit suspension orders or any documents that would warrant the non-imposition of liquidated damages to the concerned contractor to the Office of the Municipal Accountant copy furnished the Audit Team, if any. Otherwise, direct the Municipal Accountant to compute the liquidated damages for the abovementioned project;

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to require the concerned Contractors to submit an irrevocable standby letters of credit of from a commercial bank, bank guarantees or surety bonds callable on demand equivalent to the retention money of 10 per cent of the 50 per cent of the value of works and furnish the Auditor a copy thereof and require the Municipal Accountant to deduct retention money of 10 per cent from every progress payment until 50 per cent of the value of works, as determined by the procuring entity, are completed. If, after 50 per cent completion, the work is satisfactorily done and on schedule, no additional retention shall be made; otherwise, the 10 per cent retention shall be imposed.

Exert extra caution or close watch with the details of performance securities, surety bonds and other documents, particularly, its validity;


Maximize the conduct of Pre-bid Conference to minimize the chances or possibilities of bidders’ disqualification due to non-compliance with the bidding requirements; and 

Direct the BAC to submit promptly all contracts with their supporting documents to the Audit Team for review within five days from perfection thereof in compliance with existing regulations. Likewise, request for technical inspection for completed projects must be submitted to the COA.

Instruct the BAC to require the suppliers to indicate in their quotation the complete and specific technical specification, particularly the brand of items offered in the bid in compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-001; 

Require the Inspectorate Team to cross verify the actual items delivered to the delivery invoice during receipt of the items and assure compliance with the required documentation under Section 9.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001; and

Furnish the Audit Team a consolidated file of recurring documents from supplier during procurement such as Mayor’s permit, etc., if any, which was found lacking as discussed in the observation.

We recommended that Management:

Submit valid justification on why eligibility documents of the contractors were subscribed and sworn, notarized, issued and/or furnished after the deadline of submission of bids and/or opening of bids;
Submit valid justification on why the opening of bids of the various projects were not conducted on the same day or immediately after the deadline of the submission of bids;
Submit valid justification on why the projects were advertised despite the availability of Philippine Government Electronic Procurement System   (PhilGEPS); and
Require the BAC to strictly adhere with the provision of the 2016 R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended the Management to:
Review the schedules and subsidiaries to ensure proper presentation of schedules of accounts in the FS;
Ensure that any funds accruing to the barangays of the Municipality are transferred to them on a timely basis;
Through the Municipal Treasurer, inform the parties with stale checks of their claim from the Municipality; and
Revert back to the GF payables falling under the criteria in Section 98 of Presidential Decree (P.D.) No. 1445.

We recommended that  Management, in strict compliance with rules set forth by R.A. No. 9184:
Avoid accepting eligibility requirements after the deadline of submission of bids;
Use non-discretionary pass/fail criteria especially during bid evaluation and/or opening of bids, and during post-qualification;
Ensure that all process and/or procedures before contract signing have taken place prior entering into contract;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit suspension orders or any documents that would warrant the non-imposition of liquidated damages to the concerned contractor to the Office of the Municipal Accountant copy furnished the Audit Team, if any. Otherwise, direct the Municipal Accountant to compute the liquidated damages for the abovementioned project;
Direct the BAC to require the concerned Contractors to submit an irrevocable standby letters of credit of from a commercial bank, bank guarantees or surety bonds callable on demand equivalent to the retention money of 10 per cent of the 50 per cent of the value of works and furnish the Auditor a copy thereof and require the Municipal Accountant to deduct retention money of 10 per cent from every progress payment until 50 per cent of the value of works, as determined by the procuring entity, are completed.  If, after 50 per cent completion, the work is satisfactorily done and on schedule, no additional retention shall be made; otherwise, the 10 per cent retention shall be imposed;
Exert extra caution or close watch with the details of performance securities, surety bonds and other documents, particularly, its validity;
Maximize the conduct of Pre-bid Conference to minimize the chances or possibilities of bidders’ disqualification due to non-compliance with the bidding requirements; and
Direct the BAC to submit promptly all contracts with their supporting documents to the Audit Team for review within five days from perfection thereof in compliance with existing regulations. Likewise, request for technical inspection for completed projects must be submitted to the Commission on Audit.

We recommended that Management:
Submit valid justification on why eligibility documents of the contractors were subscribed and sworn, notarized, issued and/or furnished after the deadline of submission of bids and/or opening of bids;
Submit valid justification on why the opening of bids of the various projects were not conducted on the same day or immediately after the deadline of the submission of bids;
Submit valid justification on why the projects were advertised on the newspaper of general circulation despite the availability of Philgeps; and
Require the BAC to strictly adhere with the provision of the 2016 R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly adhere to the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; 




Prepare, submit and implement the 10-year SWM Plan that will address the solid waste issues; 


Require the SMW Board, with collaboration with the SB to formulate and enact a SWM ordinances particularly promoting, among others, Section 10 of R.A. No. 9003; and

Take appropriate actions that would lead to the safe closure and rehabilitation of the open dumpsite and switch to sanitary landfill.

